name: Lampropeltis elapsoides (Holbrook, 1838)
occurrenceRemarks: Two large Scarlet Kingsnakes found on separate driveways by my dad! We took them to our backyard for photos and found a nice spot to release them. Final 3 photos are of the smaller of the two. It had several kinks near the cloaca, and had more bands than the other one. Looks like one I've seen before. Edit: after comparing photos, this is the same snake I found on July 31st and August 30th of 2022, so it has been doing quite well over the past 2 years. Much larger now.

name: Lampropeltis elapsoides (Holbrook, 1838)
occurrenceRemarks: The second of the two scarlet Kingsnakes. This one had less banding, duller yellows, and was a bit larger than the first. It bite the other snake when they were both in my hand, but quickly let go after I released them. Then the other one bit me as payback...

name: Lampropeltis elapsoides (Holbrook, 1838)
occurrenceRemarks: A handsome 19-inch (+/-) specimen encountered late afternoon by my son Josh and myself on the Flagler Trail, about half a mile south of the Little Big Econ. Squirmed and bit initially and then settled down, with continual tongue probing every few seconds. Released where caught. Appeared content to remain on the trail, so a little foot nudging was required to prompt it off-path and out of harm's way from oncoming cyclists and hikers.

name: Lampropeltis elapsoides (Holbrook, 1838)
occurrenceRemarks: This snake was found under a propane storage tank outside of a gas station on a warm humid night. The snake was simply curled up resting underneath this shelter. Class: Reptilia, scales Order: Squamata, snake or lizard Suborder: Serpentes, snake Family: Colubridae, smooth appearance Since this is visibly a snake (and not a limbless lizard due to lack of external ears) is can be placed down to Serpentes. The family colubridae is broad but this snake shares some common traits of the family like smooth scales.
